  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "9. (1Ti 1:15). This verse (Greek), \"faithful is the saying, \" &c. confirms the assertion as to the \"promise\" attached to \"godliness,\" 1Ti 4:8, and forms a prefatory introduction to 1Ti 4:10, which is joined to 1Ti 4:9 by \"For.\" So 2Ti 2:11. Godly men seem to suffer loss as to this life: Paul hereby refutes the notion [Bengel]. \"God is the Saviour specially of those that believe\" (1Ti 4:10), both as to \"the life that now is,\" and also as to \"the life which is to come\" (1Ti 4:8).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This saying about the advantage of godliness is true, and worthy to be received of all men. See the notes on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Timothy 1:15",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Timothy 1:15",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the same words are applied to the great proposition of the gospel: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "That Christ came into the world to save sinners.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " That Christ came into the world to save sinners, and that such sinners as from ungodly will become godly, and persevere in the practice of godliness, shall be happy in this life, and saved in the life to come, are two faithful and remarkable sayings, worthy the acceptation of all reasonable creatures. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
